"1305–1346":"1305–1346","–Female":"Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1329–Male":"1329–Deceased","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","abt. 1329":"about 1329","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","about 1309":"about 1309","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1310":"about 1310","about 1286":"about 1286","about 1287":"about 1287","1329":"1329","of Denton, Yorksshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Denton, Yorks., Eng.":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vavasour","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: status name for a feudal tenant ranking immediately below a baron, Old French  <i>vavas(s)our</i>,  <i>vavasseur</i>, Latin  <i>vassus vassorum</i> ‘vassal of vassals’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vavasseur","meanings":["English:  see  Vavasour  ."]},{"name":"Bavister","meanings":["English:   Titford   suggests that this is a late variant of   Vavasour  . It would be a dissimilated form of  <i>Vavister</i> and  <i>Vavester</i>, variants of  <i>Vavasour</i> that are evidenced in Lincs, also in Cambs, whence the name spread into Beds. Compare Willa Vavister, 1579 in   IGI   (Scopwick, Lincs); Thomas Vavister, 1615 in   IGI   (Cranwell, Lincs); Mary Vavester, 1708, Joseph Vavisor, 1738 in   IGI   (New Sleaford, Lincs)."]},{"name":"Vawser","meanings":["English: reduced form of   Vavasour  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Le Vavasour was born about 1287, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Mauger le Vavasour, was 24 and his mother, Alice Revell, was 24. He married Agnes Grimston about 1309, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1287–":"umbes 1287–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1305–1346":"1305–1346","–Female":"Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","abt. 1329":"umbes 1329","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","about 1309":"umbes 1309","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1286":"umbes 1286","about 1287":"umbes 1287","1329":"1329","of Denton, Yorksshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Denton, Yorks., Eng.":"Denton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1287–":"noin 1287–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1305–1346":"1305–1346","–Female":"Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","abt. 1329":"noin 1329","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","about 1309":"noin 1309","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1310":"noin 1310","about 1286":"noin